@node Manual Installation
@subsection Manual Installation

First clone the Git repository, then, in your Emacs initialization file, add Nael to @code{load-path} and load it.  For lazy loading the autoloads-file needs to be build beforehand.

@lisp
;; git clone https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git ~/path/to/nael

(add-to-list 'load-path "~/path/to/nael/nael")
;; (add-to-list 'load-path "~/path/to/nael/nael-lsp")

;; Option 1, eager loading:
(require 'nael)
;; (require 'nael-lsp)

;; Option 2, lazy loading:
;; cd ~/path/to/nael && ./build.el autoloads
;; (require 'nael-autoloads)
;; (require 'nael-lsp-autoloads)

;; Optionally, make readme available as info manual:
(require 'info)
(info-initialize)
(add-to-list 'Info-directory-list "~/path/to/nael/nael")
@end lisp

@node Installation via @code{package-vc}
@subsection Installation via @code{package-vc}

Since version 29 from 2023, Emacs ships with @code{package-vc} which enables the built-in package manager @code{package} to install from version-controlled source repositories.  Keep in mind to regularly upgrade such packages with the command @code{package-vc-upgrade} or @code{package-vc-upgrade-all}.  (And please ignore the warnings that arise when @code{package-vc} attempts to byte-compile all Elisp source files in the repository instead of just the package-specific ones.)

@enumerate
@item
@anchor{Installation via @code{package-vc-selected-packages}}Installation via @code{package-vc-selected-packages}


In your Emacs session, select packages per @code{package-vc-selected-packages} variable and install them with @samp{M-x package-vc-install-selected-packages RET}.  Persist the package selection in your Emacs initialization file too.  @code{package-vc} will generate the autoloads-file automatically.  To lazy-load Nael, load the autoloads-file.

@lisp
(require 'package-vc)

(setopt package-vc-selected-packages
        '((nael
           :doc "nael/README.org"
           :lisp-dir "nael"
           :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git")
       ;; (nael-lsp
       ;;  :lisp-dir "nael-lsp"
       ;;  :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git")
          ))

(package-initialize)

;; Option 1, lazy loading:
(require 'nael-autoloads)
;; (require 'nael-lsp-autoloads)

;; Option 2, eager loading:
;; (require 'nael)
;; (require 'nael-lsp)
@end lisp

@item
@anchor{Installation via @code{use-package} @samp{vc}}Installation via @code{use-package} @samp{:vc}


Since version 30 from 2025, Emacs' popular @code{use-package} macro supports a @samp{:vc} keyword as interface to @code{package-vc}.  (Because each package has autoload-cookies on relevant expressions, and because @code{use-package} will load the autoloads-file that is generated at installation, you don't need to specify load-triggers like @samp{:mode}.  I.e. lazy-loading should work out of the box.)

@lisp
(use-package nael
  :vc ( :doc "nael/README.org"
        :lisp-dir "nael"
        :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git"))

;; (use-package nael-lsp
;;   :after nael
;;   :vc ( :lisp-dir "nael-lsp"
;;         :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git"))
@end lisp
@end enumerate

@node Usage
@chapter Usage

Language Server Protocol (LSP):

@itemize
@item
@samp{C-c C-e} (@code{eglot}) starts Eglot, the LSP client.
@item
@samp{C-h .} (@code{eldoc-doc-buffer}) displays the ElDoc documentation buffer showing tactic state and expected goal at point.
@item
@samp{C-c C-l} (@code{lsp}) starts lsp-mode, an alternative LSP client.  The key is only bound if @code{nael-lsp} is autoloaded.
@end itemize

Abbreviations:

@itemize
@item
@samp{C-c C-a} (@code{abbrev-mode}) enables abbreviations.
@item
@samp{C-c C-k} (@code{nael-abbrev-help}) echoes abbreviations that expand to the character at point, or, if active, to the selected region.
@item
@samp{C-x '} (@code{expand-abbrev}) expands the abbreviation before point without any inserting any character.  (Usually, you'd insert a space or newline to expand.)
@end itemize

Build:

@itemize
@item
@samp{C-c C-c} (@code{project-compile}) prompts for a command to build the current project.  It will suggest @samp{lake build} because Nael configures the @code{compile-command} variable.
@end itemize

Navigation:

@itemize
@item
@samp{M-a} (@code{forward-sentence}) go to beginning of current sentence/block, or to previous one.
@item
@samp{M-e} (@code{backward-sentence}) go to end of current sentence/block, or to next one.
@item
@samp{M-g i} (@code{imenu}) jumps to an interactively chosen definition in current buffer.
@end itemize

Comments:

@itemize
@item
@samp{M-;} (@code{comment-dwim}) toggles the active region as comment or, if no region is active, creates a comment at end of line.
@item
@samp{M-q} (@code{prog-fill-reindent-defun}) fills the string- or comment-paragraph at point, or reindents the point-surrounding code.
@end itemize

@node Configuration
@chapter Configuration

To view the complete list of Nael's user option variables from within Emacs, customize the group @code{nael} (and its child-groups) with @samp{M-x customize-group RET nael RET}.  This chapter highlights and explains some user options by examples.

As an exception, Emacs customization groups cannot include keymaps.  You can bind custom keys in @code{nael-mode-map} like this:

@lisp
(keymap-set nael-mode-map "C-c ." #'highlight-symbol-at-point)
@end lisp

To automatically enable features (e.g. abbreviations, Eglot or lsp-mode) when Nael is started, customize @code{nael-mode-hook} as follows:

@lisp
(add-hook 'nael-mode-hook #'abbrev-mode)
(add-hook 'nael-mode-hook #'eglot-ensure)
@end lisp

Nael's Abbrev tables use the @samp{:regexp} property which is @uref{https://github.com/minad/cape/discussions/158#discussioncomment-14687758, incompatible} with @uref{https://github.com/company-mode/company-mode, Company}'s @code{company-abbrev} and @uref{https://github.com/minad/cape, Cape}'s @code{cape-abbrev}.  Instead, Nael supports completion-at-point natively via @code{nael-abbrev-capf}.  This CAPF is buffer-locally added to @code{completion-at-point-functions} whenever Abbrev mode is enabled inside Nael.  To ditch this feature, set the @code{nael-abbrev-capf} variable to @samp{nil}.

